00:01:37.534 --> 00:01:38.950
So what I want to
do in this video

00:01:38.950 --> 00:01:40.930
is think about
what's going on here.

00:01:40.930 --> 00:01:43.000
And what I'm actually
drawing, if we just

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
keep on doing this
forever and forever,

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.990
every side, every iteration,
we look at each side,

00:01:47.990 --> 00:01:49.520
we divide into
three equal sides.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:52.177
And then the next iteration,
or three equal segments,

00:01:52.177 --> 00:01:53.760
the next iteration,
the middle segment

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:55.799
we turn to another
equilateral triangle.

00:01:55.799 --> 00:01:57.590
This shape that we're
describing right here

00:01:57.590 --> 00:01:59.950
is called a Koch snowflake.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.300
And I'm sure I'm
mispronouncing the Koch part.

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:05.480
A Koch snowflake,
and it was first

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:08.229
described by this gentleman
right over here, who

00:02:08.229 --> 00:02:11.270
is a Swedish mathematician,
Niels Fabian Helge von

00:02:11.270 --> 00:02:14.610
Koch, who I'm sure
I'm mispronouncing it.

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:17.740
And this was one of the
earliest described fractals.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:19.690
So this is a fractal.

00:02:19.690 --> 00:02:22.120
And the reason why it
is considered a fractal

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:24.890
is that it looks the same,
or it looks very similar,

00:02:24.890 --> 00:02:26.630
on any scale you look at it.

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:29.591
So when you look at it at this
scale, so if you look at this,

00:02:29.591 --> 00:02:31.090
it like you see a
bunch of triangles

00:02:31.090 --> 00:02:32.320
with some bumps on it.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:35.130
But then if you were to
zoom in right over there,

00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:38.190
then you would still see
that same type of pattern.

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:39.926
And then if you were
to zoom in again,

00:02:39.926 --> 00:02:41.300
you would see it
again and again.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:43.320
So a fractal is anything
that at on any scale,

00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:46.770
on any level of zoom, it kind
of looks roughly the same.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:48.270
So that's why it's
called a fractal.

00:02:48.270 --> 00:02:49.790
Now what's particularly
interesting,

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:53.700
and why I'm putting it at this
point in the geometry playlist,

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.417
is that this actually has
an infinite perimeter.

00:02:56.417 --> 00:02:58.500
If you were to keep doing
it, if you were actually

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:00.690
to make the Koch
snowflake, where

00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:04.130
you keep an infinite number
of times on every smaller

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:05.840
little triangle
here, you keep adding

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:09.754
another equilateral
triangle on its side.

00:03:09.754 --> 00:03:11.670
And to show that it has
an infinite perimeter,

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:13.890
let's just consider
one side over here.

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:15.960
So let's say that
this side, so let's

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.024
say we're starting
right when we started

00:03:18.024 --> 00:03:19.940
with that original
triangle, that's that side.

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:21.565
Let's say it has length s.

00:03:21.565 --> 00:03:23.565
And then we divide it
into three equal segments.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:29.910
So those are going to
be s/3, s/3-- actually,

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:31.670
let me write it this way.

00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:36.170
s/3, s/3, and s/3.

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.730
And in the middle segment, you
make an equilateral triangle.

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:44.462
So each of these sides
are going to be s/3.

00:03:44.462 --> 00:03:47.290
s/3, s/3.

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:51.472
And now the length of this new
part-- I can't call it a line

00:03:51.472 --> 00:03:53.180
anymore, because it
has this bump in it--

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:57.580
the length of this part right
over here, this side, now

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:01.510
doesn't have just a length
of s, it is now s/3 times 4.

00:04:01.510 --> 00:04:03.160
Before it was s/3 times 3.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:07.730
Now you have 1, 2, 3, 4
segments that are s/3.

00:04:07.730 --> 00:04:10.400
So now, after one
time, after one pace,

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:15.160
after one time of doing
this adding triangles,

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.480
our new side, after
we add that bump,

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:20.760
is going to be four times s/3.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.730
Or it equals 4/3 s.

00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:28.670
So if our original
perimeter when it was just

00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:31.100
a triangle is p sub 0.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:33.930
After one pass, after
we add one set of bumps,

00:04:33.930 --> 00:04:39.840
then our perimeter is going to
be 4/3 times the original one.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:42.630
Because each of the sides are
going to be 4/3 bigger now.

00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:44.610
So this was made
up of three sides.

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:46.870
Now each of those sides
are going to be 4/3 bigger.

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:49.400
So the new perimeter's
going to be 4/3 times that.

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:51.680
And then when we take
a second pass on it,

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:54.740
it's going to be 4/3
times this first pass.

00:04:54.740 --> 00:04:57.650
So every pass you take,
it's getting 4/3 bigger.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:00.380
Or it's getting, I guess,
a 1/3 bigger on every,

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:03.437
it's getting 4/3
the previous pass.

00:05:03.437 --> 00:05:05.520
And so if you do that an
infinite number of times,

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:09.220
if you multiply any
number by 4/3 an

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.180
infinite number of
times, you're going

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:13.820
to get an infinite number
of infinite length.

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:16.274
So P infinity.

00:05:16.274 --> 00:05:18.690
The perimeter, if you do this
an infinite number of times,

00:05:18.690 --> 00:05:20.370
is infinite.

00:05:20.370 --> 00:05:21.920
Now that by itself
is kind of cool,

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.461
just to think about something
that has an infinite perimeter.

00:05:24.461 --> 00:05:28.192
But what's even neater is that
it actually has a finite area.

00:05:28.192 --> 00:05:29.900
And when I say a finite
area, it actually

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:32.164
covers a bounded
amount of space.

00:05:32.164 --> 00:05:34.080
And I could actually
draw a shape around this,

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.120
and this thing will
never expand beyond that.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:37.620
And to think about
it, I'm not going

00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:39.240
to do a really
formal proof, just

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:42.520
think about it, what happens
on any one of these sides.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.630
So on that first pass we
have that this triangle

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:46.010
gets popped out.

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:49.340
And then, if you think about it,
if you just draw what happens,

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:51.681
the next iteration you draw
these two triangles right

00:05:51.681 --> 00:05:52.180
over there.

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:54.270
And these two characters
right over there.

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:56.330
And then you put some
triangles over here,

00:05:56.330 --> 00:05:58.520
and here, and here,
and here, and here.

00:05:58.520 --> 00:05:59.700
So on and so forth.

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:01.960
But notice, you can keep
adding more and more.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.630
You can add essentially an
infinite number of these bumps,

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:07.380
but you're never going to
go past this original point.

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.490
And the same thing is going
to be true on this side

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:11.540
right over here.

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:14.240
It's also going to be true
of this side over here.

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:16.920
Also going to be true
at this side over here.

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.680
Also going to be true
this side over there.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.130
And then also going to be
true that side over there.

00:06:22.130 --> 00:06:24.750
So even if you do this an
infinite number of times,

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:27.450
this shape, this Koch
snowflake will never

00:06:27.450 --> 00:06:30.430
have a larger area than
this bounding hexagon.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:33.190
Or which will never have a
larger area than a shape that

00:06:33.190 --> 00:06:34.342
looks something like that.

00:06:34.342 --> 00:06:35.925
I'm just kind of
drawing an arbitrary,

00:06:35.925 --> 00:06:38.070
well I want to make it
